<i> They're 55 and 60 years old,</i>

00:10:19.384 --> 00:10:21.653 line:0%
<i> well beyond their expected
 life span.</i>

00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:25.757 line:0%
<i>In addition, wood beams holding
 up the tunnels are eroding,</i>

00:10:25.858 --> 00:10:29.595 line:0%
<i>and what corrodes timber beams?
 Radiation.</i>

00:10:30.262 --> 00:10:31.163
Yeah!

00:10:31.397 --> 00:10:33.933
You can't build something
out of wood and expect it

00:10:34.033 --> 00:10:36.101
to last forever. You're supposed
to have learned that

00:10:36.201 --> 00:10:38.570
from the second dumbest
of the Three Little Pigs.

00:10:38.770 --> 00:10:40.405
(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

00:10:40.706 --> 00:10:43.309
Hanford... Hanford is
a gigantic problem.

00:10:43.709 --> 00:10:46.846
And even though it hasn't
produced anything for 30 years,

00:10:46.946 --> 00:10:48.380
the Department of Energy
still spends

00:10:48.481 --> 00:10:50.248
nearly two and a half billion
dollars a year

00:10:50.348 --> 00:10:53.085
on cleaning it up, which is
close to ten percent

00:10:53.185 --> 00:10:54.486
of its annual budget.

00:10:54.853 --> 00:10:56.154
And it is pretty weird

00:10:56.455 --> 00:10:58.457
to find out that a place
you just heard about

00:10:58.690 --> 00:11:00.893
is getting that much
of the DOE's money.

00:11:01.126 --> 00:11:03.728
It's like finding out that half
the Department of Agriculture

00:11:03.828 --> 00:11:06.265
budget goes to this moose
named Gordon.

00:11:06.498 --> 00:11:09.068
I mean, I don't know
the right amount,

00:11:09.668 --> 00:11:11.870
-but that seems like a lot.
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

00:11:11.970 --> 00:11:14.039
And in case you're thinking,
"Well I'm definitely glad that

00:11:14.139 --> 00:11:15.507
I don't live near Hanford,"

00:11:15.607 --> 00:11:18.243
remember there are nuclear
power plants storing waste

00:11:18.610 --> 00:11:20.779
all over the country,
lots of it in so-called

00:11:21.080 --> 00:11:22.481
"spent fuel pools."

00:11:22.581 --> 00:11:25.017
That's where nuclear
fuel rods are supposed to be

00:11:25.117 --> 00:11:26.785
temporarily placed to cool down,

00:11:26.885 --> 00:11:28.887
and then put
into dry containers,

00:11:29.121 --> 00:11:30.055
and then moved

00:11:30.155 --> 00:11:31.990
to permanent
underground storage sites.

00:11:32.090 --> 00:11:34.359
But remember,
we don't have one of those.

00:11:34.626 --> 00:11:37.395
And in many places those pools
are just accumulating

00:11:37.495 --> 00:11:38.663
more and more rods.

00:11:38.764 --> 00:11:40.399
And while experts say
it's highly unlikely,

00:11:40.499 --> 00:11:43.836
if a Fukushima-like accident
happens at one of those,

00:11:43.936 --> 00:11:45.771
the results could be
catastrophic.

00:11:46.439 --> 00:11:48.507
ANCHOR:
<i> The northeast has a number
 of nuclear power plants,</i>

00:11:48.607 --> 00:11:51.877
