<i>for decades, perhaps centuries.</i>

00:12:06.258 --> 00:12:08.494
That's right,
lots of big cities.

00:12:08.594 --> 00:12:10.829
New York, Hartford, Boston.

00:12:11.029 --> 00:12:12.330
And that last one is
a real shame,

00:12:12.431 --> 00:12:14.799
'cause as I understand it,
they only just got

00:12:14.899 --> 00:12:16.168
un-racist yesterday.

00:12:16.368 --> 00:12:17.569
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)
-So...

00:12:17.669 --> 00:12:20.639
I mean, at least they could get
to enjoy their new life.

00:12:20.839 --> 00:12:22.041
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)
-So...

00:12:22.241 --> 00:12:25.143
So, look, it is pretty clear
we need to find

00:12:25.243 --> 00:12:27.946
a permanent facility to store
our most dangerous waste.

00:12:28.046 --> 00:12:30.916
And 30 years ago,
we actually settled on a site,

00:12:31.016 --> 00:12:32.818
Yucca Mountain in Nevada.

00:12:33.051 --> 00:12:34.653
Congress passed a law
designating it

00:12:34.753 --> 00:12:37.122
as our sole candidate
for waste storage.

00:12:37.222 --> 00:12:39.691
Now since then,
we've spent 15 billion dollars

00:12:39.791 --> 00:12:40.759
prepping the site,

00:12:40.860 --> 00:12:43.062
as you can see
from this rather upbeat video.

00:12:51.103 --> 00:12:52.904
NARRATOR:<i> Located
 about 100 miles</i>

00:12:53.004 --> 00:12:54.373
<i> northwest of Las Vegas,</i>

00:12:54.673 --> 00:12:57.209
<i> Yucca mountain is the most
 thoroughly researched site</i>

00:12:57.309 --> 00:12:58.677
<i> of its kind in the world.</i>

00:12:58.777 --> 00:13:01.113
<i> Experts throughout the world
 agree that the most</i>

00:13:01.213 --> 00:13:02.881
<i> feasible and safe method</i>

00:13:02.981 --> 00:13:05.618
<i> for disposing
of highly radioactive materials</i>

00:13:06.452 --> 00:13:08.520
<i> is to store them
 deep underground.</i>

00:13:09.054 --> 00:13:10.556
That's right.
The best place

00:13:10.656 --> 00:13:13.258
to put nuclear waste is
in a hole deep underground.

00:13:13.358 --> 00:13:14.759
Much like Felicity.

00:13:15.293 --> 00:13:18.296
Wait. Wait, if she's not there,
where is she?

00:13:18.397 --> 00:13:20.933
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)
-Ah, Jesus fucking Christ!

00:13:21.333 --> 00:13:22.133
Fuck me!

00:13:22.233 --> 00:13:24.236
Jesus! Fucking--
Get the fuck away!

00:13:25.036 --> 00:13:27.039
(PANTING)

00:13:27.439 --> 00:13:29.074
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

00:13:29.841 --> 00:13:32.177
(PANTING)

00:13:32.511 --> 00:13:33.745
-(AUDIENCE CHEERS)
-It's alright. It's okay.

00:13:33.845 --> 00:13:34.780
I'm fine.

00:13:35.581 --> 00:13:36.448
It's fine.

00:13:38.584 --> 00:13:39.584
The point is...

00:13:40.619 --> 00:13:43.755
So, Yucca mountain
is our permanent storage site.

00:13:43.855 --> 00:13:46.225
So the problem is solved,
right? Well, no!

00:13:46.425 --> 00:13:48.327
Because while the site
has been deemed safe,

00:13:48.427 --> 00:13:49.961
and the people
in the immediate area,

00:13:50.061 --> 00:13:52.397
Nye County,
actually support the project,

00:13:52.497 --> 00:13:54.132
many Nevadans elsewhere
in the state

00:13:54.332 --> 00:13:55.867
really don't want it.

00:13:55.967 --> 00:13:58.336
And their former senator,
Harry Reed, lobbied hard,

00:13:58.437 --> 00:14:00.672
eventually managing
to get Yucca shot down.

00:14:00.772 --> 00:14:03.275
Now, to be fair, he did have
an alternative plan

00:14:03.375 --> 00:14:05.311
for all the states sitting
on their nuclear waste,

00:14:05.411 --> 00:14:06.612
but to put it mildly,

00:14:06.812 --> 00:14:08.747
it was not exactly
scientifically-sound.

00:14:09.415 --> 00:14:10.916 line:0%
Leave it on site, where it is.

00:14:11.016 --> 00:14:13.785
Leave it where it is,
and dry cast storage containers.

00:14:14.052 --> 00:14:16.455 line:0%
If you were smart,
what you would do is, uh...

00:14:16.689 --> 00:14:17.857 line:0%
leave this...

00:14:18.524 --> 00:14:19.658 line:0%
leave it where it is.

00:14:19.758 --> 00:14:20.792
(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

00:14:20.892 --> 00:14:23.028
"If you're smart,
what you would do is leave

00:14:23.128 --> 00:14:25.830
the thing where it is"
is terrible advice

00:14:25.931 --> 00:14:26.998
for dealing with nuclear waste.

00:14:27.098 --> 00:14:28.533
Although, it is coincidentally

00:14:28.633 --> 00:14:30.936
the title of Britain's
bestselling book on parenting.

00:14:31.370 --> 00:14:32.871
-But... But...
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

00:14:33.138 --> 00:14:34.639
Here... Here is the truth.

00:14:35.006 --> 00:14:37.275
the scientific consensus
for decades

00:14:37.375 --> 00:14:41.279
has been that leaving it where
it is is a really bad idea.

00:14:41.379 --> 00:14:44.016
The shutted power plant
at San Onofre, in California,

00:14:44.116 --> 00:14:46.652
is storing nuclear waste,
and it's on a fault line

00:14:46.852 --> 00:14:48.520
right next to the ocean.

00:14:48.887 --> 00:14:50.389
And that sounds like
something you learn

00:14:50.489 --> 00:14:52.357
in the first scene of a movie
starring The Rock

00:14:52.457 --> 00:14:54.025
that you watch on a plane.

00:14:54.126 --> 00:14:55.160
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)
-And look,

00:14:55.260 --> 00:14:57.262
maybe Yucca is the best place

00:14:57.362 --> 00:14:59.631
to store our growing supply
of radioactive garbage.

00:14:59.831 --> 00:15:00.733
Maybe it's not.

00:15:01.166 --> 00:15:04.069
I am not a nuclear scientist.
I just have the face of one.

00:15:04.369 --> 00:15:06.071
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)
-And... And our--

00:15:06.438 --> 00:15:09.007
Our new energy secretary,
Rick Perry...

00:15:09.207 --> 00:15:10.508
yes, Rick Perry...

00:15:10.842 --> 00:15:12.878
has said that he is
optimistic about fixing

00:15:12.978 --> 00:15:14.412
the whole problem,
which does sound great.

00:15:14.512 --> 00:15:16.615
Although, he didn't exactly do
a great job

00:15:16.715 --> 00:15:18.216
at dealing with this disaster.

00:15:18.683 --> 00:15:20.052
♪ (UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

00:15:20.252 --> 00:15:22.554
(STUDIO AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

00:15:23.188 --> 00:15:25.324
Yeah, that was him
on<i> Dancing with the Stars,</i>

00:15:25.424 --> 00:15:27.993
and on the basis of that,
managing volatile energy

00:15:28.093 --> 00:15:29.828
is not really his forte.

00:15:30.629 --> 00:15:32.197
But here's the thing.
We've been saying

00:15:32.298 --> 00:15:34.533
that we are going to fix this
for decades now,

00:15:34.633 --> 00:15:36.768
and we seem to be no closer
to a solution.

00:15:36.868 --> 00:15:37.770
And let me show you something

00:15:37.870 --> 00:15:39.371
that really drove that fact
home to us,

00:15:39.471 --> 00:15:40.906
because we've
been researching this story

00:15:41.006 --> 00:15:43.609
for a couple of weeks now,
and just yesterday afternoon,

00:15:43.976 --> 00:15:47.345
we stumbled on a TV special
from 1977,

00:15:47.445 --> 00:15:48.580
the year that I was born.

00:15:49.548 --> 00:15:52.418
♪ (MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

00:15:55.353 --> 00:15:56.922
NARRATOR:
<i> NBC News presents...</i>

00:16:00.358 --> 00:16:02.428
Danger! Radioactive Waste.

00:16:03.328 --> 00:16:05.397
Yeah, this problem is so old

00:16:05.497 --> 00:16:07.366
they reported on it back when
the news was kept

00:16:07.466 --> 00:16:09.467
in an America-shaped vault
that you had to open

00:16:09.567 --> 00:16:10.602
with a crank.

00:16:11.036 --> 00:16:13.305
As we watched that yesterday,
we gradually

00:16:13.405 --> 00:16:15.908
and chillingly realized that
by pure coincidence

00:16:16.175 --> 00:16:19.344
it hits every beat of the story
that we just told you.

00:16:19.578 --> 00:16:21.747
It opens with footage
of sailors throwing barrels

00:16:21.847 --> 00:16:22.781
into the ocean.

00:16:22.881 --> 00:16:24.883
It looks at the facilities
at Hanford.

00:16:25.117 --> 00:16:27.452
It talks about radiation's
impact on workers

00:16:27.685 --> 00:16:29.354
and on families
who live nearby.

00:16:29.554 --> 00:16:31.523
And while it doesn't have
a radioactive alligator,

00:16:31.724 --> 00:16:33.658
it does have radioactive cows.

00:16:33.925 --> 00:16:35.761
Which is-- which is still good.
Although,

00:16:35.861 --> 00:16:38.029
I did prefer our alligator.

00:16:38.230 --> 00:16:40.299
I liked it when he went...
(HISSES)

00:16:40.399 --> 00:16:41.500
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)
-But--

00:16:41.833 --> 00:16:43.268
But the most chilling moment

00:16:43.501 --> 00:16:46.004
in that documentary might be
the one where they sit down

00:16:46.105 --> 00:16:48.239
with someone in authority,
and demand to know

00:16:48.339 --> 00:16:50.075
exactly when this will be fixed.

00:16:50.375 --> 00:16:52.945
NARRATOR:<i> When you ask
when the problem will be solved,</i>

00:16:53.045 --> 00:16:54.312
<i> you get answers like this.</i>

00:16:54.946 --> 00:16:56.648
WOMAN: What's the realistic
time table?

00:16:57.515 --> 00:16:59.518 line:0%
Realistic time table
is scheduled to have

00:16:59.618 --> 00:17:02.721 line:0%
a repository in operation
by 1985,

00:17:03.188 --> 00:17:06.792
with the selection of the sites
by the end of 1978

00:17:06.892 --> 00:17:07.960
for detailed work.

00:17:08.460 --> 00:17:09.327
Exactly.

00:17:09.761 --> 00:17:12.163
Nuclear waste is a problem
we were supposed to have dealt

00:17:12.263 --> 00:17:14.833
with in the 1980's
and still cannot solve,

00:17:14.933 --> 00:17:18.670
much like this Rubik's Cube
that I always carry with me.

00:17:19.071 --> 00:17:22.541
You are my Jean Valjean,
cube, and, one day,

00:17:22.975 --> 00:17:25.243
-I shall defeat you.
-(AUDIENCE LAUGHS)

00:17:25.443 --> 00:17:27.679
And at the end
of that special, remember,

00:17:27.779 --> 00:17:31.249
40 years ago, the correspondent
delivers this special message.

00:17:31.783 --> 00:17:33.852
The waste
increases every minute.

00:17:34.553 --> 00:17:37.088
The solution of where
to put it is years away.

00:17:37.556 --> 00:17:39.525
<i> And none of the previous
 solutions has worked.</i>

00:17:40.893 --> 00:17:42.827
<i> We are accustomed
 in this country to act</i>

00:17:42.927 --> 00:17:44.763
<i> only in times of crisis.</i>

00:17:45.730 --> 00:17:47.266
<i> But with nuclear waste,</i>

00:17:47.499 --> 00:17:49.701
<i> when the crisis comes,
 it will be too late.</i>

00:17:50.402 --> 00:17:52.971
And that was
from four decades ago.

00:17:53.071 --> 00:17:56.241
We have already waited way
too long to resolve this issue.

00:17:56.341 --> 00:17:58.309
And we are dancing
with trouble here.

00:17:58.510 --> 00:18:00.345
So if any one says
the government

00:18:00.445 --> 00:18:02.147
can just continue to wait,

00:18:02.247 --> 00:18:04.916
they are much like
a house with no toilet.

00:18:05.250 --> 00:18:07.185
Absolutely full of shit.

